The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe it won't wait for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers work to the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on it on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the ČTū Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price of text here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the final steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - for some customers of the Czech mobile phone providers, text messages from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight break.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to argue that there is a lot of competition in the Czech market.
This is often the responsibility of the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably hardly find any more frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a clear price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators had to respond.
Before the entry into the market of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for long.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in winning more than 100 thousand customers and thus ascending to the five largest provider of the country.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually make their way out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to put on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar approach could be taken in the Czech Republic, as in Poland.
The press spokesperson of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, without chance, the mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile phone provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
It will be more likely to enter the market of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says a phone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press spokesperson of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has long been shown by the group GTS Nova, which wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only landline telecommunications services, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already achieved progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's press spokesperson.
Maybe better times now.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a great deal of specificity over other markets.
So far, no subject has yet addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other providers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, a virtual provider will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network.
At this moment, we must have a concrete offer to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses his attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the best from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider was more competitive, this would lead to lower prices and thus also lead to a decrease in profits.
So why make market entry easier for such a competitor?
That the providers can pull on a strand when it comes to something also demonstrates the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
The most powerful pressure towards ČTū was from the company T-Mobile when U:fon was on the market.
This also demonstrates the publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and in particular its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of ČTū, which unfortunately in Czech - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It shall have the exclusive responsibility to protect economic competition (UOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem of its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
Until now, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by suppliers' representatives.
This is more than worrying by an authority representing consumer interests and, inter alia, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "For abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already touching consistency of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same fuel price at the gas stations is certainly only chance and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter that indicate a competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so neither does it have the corresponding increased responsibility for its action on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the Telecommunications Regulatory Authority," stated Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ČTū, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position in such a market.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different perspective - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for his network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not go along with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the above-mentioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The aberration of responsibility to ČTū is then a rather common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act has not succeeded in extending the competence of ČTū to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS only have to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking at it.
First of all, the operation of some pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unobserved.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
These are usually companies operating in the multilevel marketing sector.
Private mobile telephone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts as a classic company customer to the operator, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar re-sales.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the respective society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
It is quite unlikely, however, that this is not the case with those responsible for mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not lead to any neglecting profits, at the same time they are not affected by the actual official marketing, unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very low percentage of customers.
Furthermore, they must accept that the SIM card is not running on their name in their phone, so they cannot have it fully like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers."
Even that would have to happen at least strangely to ČTū.
There is also a further question for the ÚOHS.
Before such an approach, mobile operators close their eyes, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of providers, they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been pointed out several times in the text, the entry into the market of virtual providers resulted in a significant price decline in the various services.
Practically in all countries where virtual providers have developed, the classic providers have tried to prevent their development practically more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which in no way tried to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, were particularly involved in these moments.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves all over the case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot clear up the impression that there is more than no clarity in the competences in these cases.
But let's not throw the flint in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to refusing (discrimination) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will not at last make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
