The Prague transport companies also transport on Wednesday for the first time on a chip
Wednesday October 1st, 2008 will enter the history of Prague's transport operations as a date on which the first passengers will enter a subway, tram or bus, which will carry an electronic coupon in the bag instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or one-year coupon (permanent from 1 January 2009) at the same time as they can play on their chip card, in the information centres and branches of the transport operations at the subway stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobellisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played on the opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a switch with trained staff available to travellers at these points, which advises interested parties on the internet and also puts the coupon on the map," said Martin Opatrný, spokesperson of the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on self-service machines on the opencard, which are mounted in some subway vaults.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminding of ticket users, the passengers may have noticed them at the subway stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls an automatic instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the coupon previously purchased is self-evident.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants of the Central Bohemian region reach the capital.
"In the trains that belong to the Prague integrated traffic, the train-accompanied readers have readers to check the validity of the coupons for time and time," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid. This organization sets out the schedules for the Prague transport operations.
The suburban buses have card readers at the checkout at the driver.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown by the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position at the side of the cash desk.
The driver thus controls the validity of the displayed coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the displayed coupons, it is no easier than to ask the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon is valid can return to the auto-service machines where the coupons are displayed on the card.
Here the information on the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
