Among scientists, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion for years - the swing-by anomaly.
The Swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes where they receive additional swing in the gravity field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
As a result, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the Sun probe Ulysses.
What the researchers have been wondering for years, however, is that the missiles do not behave 100 percent the way they would expect it to be according to the old-fashioned gravity law.
Rather, irregularities occur at speed.
The probes become unexpectedly faster or slower.
So far, the physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They baptized him Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that perhaps even the general relativity theory of Albert Einstein, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, could not be quite correct.
The American physicist Stephen Adler of the Princeton Institute for Advanced Study still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly with the help of the so-called dark matter that astronomers made up in the universe.
