Isabel Bayón recalls the memory of the dancer from Seville Tórtola Valencia
A flamenco dancer from Seville honors a dancer who also comes from Seville.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia: her father was Catalan (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and her mother, Andalusian (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in Triana district and when she was three years old, her family moved to London.
She was a dancer and an expert on oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, she was one of the first women to fight for the emancipation of women, such as Isadora Ducan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist, vegetarian, and was committed to the abolition of the corset, which restricted the free female movement.
Isabel Bayón was fascinated by the life of this woman who left her traces of the dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe during the period between the wars.
'I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she introduced this role to me, which seemed impossible to me.'
'We don't try to tell about her life without preserving her Esprit,' said the flamenco dancer.
Your dance bases have helped me a lot in Flamenco.
'The dance of the butterfly' seemed to me, for example, like Guajira, or 'the dance of the snake' like Tango.
Her dancing was sensual and I have been told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area', she says.
The production is based on two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerto abiera'; and with flamenco master Matilde Coral, who, in exception, wanted to work with one of her former students.
`Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I feel very honored.'
The production also counts with musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; with the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the Viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with the actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of the companion of the artists who were Divas, in which he always fell in love.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who was known in as distant places as India, the United States or Russia and also throughout Europe, although she normally lived in London.
'I wanted to recall her, because I think she's one of the women who has a huge influence on a certain era and whose works no longer know any more and therefore she's less appreciated', Bayón claims.
