The drivers who can be withdrawn due to the alcohol level will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authorities order that the driver, who had three official penalties for the alcohol level, installed in his car this system that forbids him to start the car in the drunk state. If he is alcoholic, the car does not jump.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the report of the General Public Prosecutor's Office. According to their data, it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialise the driver, which is why he receives a course for the re-education of the transport behaviour.
In addition to the Advocate General, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of the Automobiles will also participate in it.
According to statistics, between 30-75 % of drivers who were shown to be subject to alcohol influence more than once.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the breathed air and prevents car start when the driver has made alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is determined which is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by those who impose the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65 % of the regular infringements already in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, it is expected that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to the administrative sanctions for two reasons: to launch this behaviour before it became a crime.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented by ordinary means, and yet a reform of the basic law is required which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The equipment is still available in the Spanish markets, in no business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Deputies will vote tomorrow because of the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
