Discussing - From blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross's blood donation service during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994 aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to develop guidelines to prevent a further catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to report, at the time several provinces set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for the administration of blood canneds in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec began her work, barely 38% of the people had confidence in the blood-conservation system in Quebec, remember Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Due to the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood preserves and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before she proudly emphasizes that in early 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'confidence is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of human insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called for one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, which, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proved without any doubt that this disease was transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which enable the presence of the virus itself directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the time of incubation between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be demonstrated by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not see this, was substantially reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is in danger of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that you have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canned each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case where HIV was transferred over a blood can.
I think one can feel comfortable these days, if one gets a blood transfusion or writes to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion did the Chikungunya virus appear, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted over the blood by insects.
We have to monitor continuously," Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Quebec also needs to provide sufficient supply.
The demand increases because the population is ageing.
As anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebec's blood donors. '
In doing so, every healthy person who is 18 years or older, who meets the criteria of fitness, can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who provide their blood are not accepted because they are sick, for example, of AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from the blood donation for one year.
With this 3%, we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can't donate blood anymore.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep them and to get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in the blood donation,' Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood canned tissues, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cords.
In the umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand a year.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year," Dr Décary continues, which describes this navel cord blood loss program as very popular.
Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
