The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the auction bidder.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to beat themselves in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
At both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which the enemy's excess plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should cooperate against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and subsequently made its efforts.
In addition, another group was promised 15 dollars of reward, in case they came out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which had also been lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the group "respecting the loss" were ready to use higher stakes than those in the control and/or the "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions has so far only been justified by the joy of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved by the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see the doctor
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various infectious liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secretion or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to vaccination against viruses A and B anyway, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms in hepatitis A occur approximately two-three weeks after consumption of contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
After that, yellowishness occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery may take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from the far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it may lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells secretly - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups where this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Rightly recognized, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banishing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 of patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this virus-induced chronic liver inflammation, its origin and the importance of early detection.
