The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the University participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was connected to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary's sight would create a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other paintings and was felt to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and at that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were either to look at the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "in security" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "anxious", and they felt "rest and peace".
During the consideration of the religious painting, they reported more than 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
