Intelligent car imitates the flight of Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired in the creation of new accident-avoiding systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system controlled by auto robots, a mini-car equipped with bees' properties, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection sign", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a field of vision of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to the board, which immediately initiates the collision-preventing process.
The obstacle is recorded in second-break parts, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it wasn't, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most internal and vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of bees when they avoid other bees.
And that must be in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, it can only be two-dimensional, not up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While the bees here are infinitely open to many possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotational motion, or the acceleration and brake.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh said it comes to the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It doesn't have to save it, or by using previous maneuvers to produce an intuitive, logical reaction, so that it is constantly using only a handful of KB memory.
There's no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
