"The vast majority of Roma youth do not have secondary education, and due to poor primary education, only a small part of them can reach a higher education degree."
Járóka also stressed that education is a fundamental human right, a key role in the exercise of other human rights.
Investment in the early training of Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU Member States.
In the view of the honourable Members, it is important that these links become as broad as possible, i.e. Roma and non-Roma.
Because the earlier a Roma student starts school, the stronger his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market, and through income and turnover taxes, they contribute to national expenditure.
"As citizens of the Union, Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - the poor and segregated education must be discontinued" - says Lívia Járóka.
As the Members said, a common, objective and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary in order to speed up the deregulation process in the education sector, which requires proper compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunity to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," said Járóka.
Since last year's Berlin Congress, the summit has been organised annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the preparation of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at European and national level, within the meaning of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
