Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historical cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favoured multiplex kinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of excluding the cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-sal complexes in the periphery, means long-term death for the one-sal cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
Most of the historical places affected are full of memories, "It is like losing a friend with whom you have left a piece of road full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which brought him 20 years ago the Oscar and the great price of Cannes. It is about the history of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
The figures supplied by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the vast amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these tokens paid mostly the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This is evidenced by the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex kinos, because they are precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been recorded: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy is leading the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the first thing is the preservation of the already existing one, because a hall in the city closes, not all of its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the lack of budget for the fund of the trade association remains clear: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros in the year would be necessary".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinemas, has decided to protect them by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures foreseen are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as advantages for the public in relation to local transport: it will be allowed to travel to the restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It's a delightful initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and in addition, I will design new concepts.
But surely we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because finally the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
