When the energy comes out of the waves, the big ones suddenly run up
It is a non-distinguishing source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface and only now does this seem to be understood by the major energy companies in the world.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and are also looking to occupate, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not by chance, these studies have been considerably intensified since the first oil crisis.
As the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gasped, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract in 2005 for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy generation.
"Chevron investigates these technologies," says the spokesperson of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, and weighs the opportunity to work with us."
This is about the procurement of an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off Alaska's coast.
This is not an underestimable sign, especially considering that oil is still being promoted by the US in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which invest in the new industry, are also not familiar with the details, so observers speak of an increasing interest.
Further improved technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still under way, not least because the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and also Scotland are of rather small dimensions and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it takes technologies with far greater environmental impact.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected bows.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the bows up and down, is transformed into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
It drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for the state permit. Part of the energy obtained could also serve military facilities.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a park latz with the help of underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Production Research, a particular interest is presently worthy of the potential that lies in the tides.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
Tidal energy is what led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
